:QUOTE
One person, one niche, one clear offer. That is a real business.

:INFO
One-Person Software Agency
A one-person agency focused on a specific niche and deliverable can generate strong revenue without employees. Positioning, pricing, and process are the three levers that determine success.

:COUNTER.half
3 Clients
Maximum concurrent projects for sustainable solo delivery
|
:COUNTER.half
5,000 USD
Minimum project size worth taking on as a solo agency

:PATH
Position Phase
Pick a niche where you have deep familiarity. Narrow the offer to one deliverable type. Generic agencies compete on price; specialists compete on expertise.

:PATH
Acquire Phase
Content marketing, referrals, and direct outreach are the three channels that work for solo agencies. Pick one and go deep for 90 days.

:PATH
Deliver Phase
Build repeatable delivery systems: proposal templates, onboarding checklists, weekly update formats, and retrospective frameworks. Reuse everything.

:CHECKLIST
Agency Operations Checklist
[ ] Write a one-sentence positioning statement
[ ] Define the core deliverable and scope boundaries
[ ] Set project and retainer pricing
[ ] Create proposal and contract templates
[ ] Set up a project management system
[ ] Build a client onboarding checklist
[ ] Define communication cadence with clients
[ ] Schedule quarterly pricing review

:NOTE
Retainers are more valuable than projects. A client paying 2,000 USD per month for six months is worth more than a 5,000 USD one-time project. Structure your offers to convert project clients into retainer clients after the first delivery.